issue.title: Use MlasConv for 1D convolutions

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Use the existing 2D convolution code in MlasConv to also handle 1D convolutions. This avoids the overhead of the generic ND im2col path as well as inheriting the threaded im2col implementation.

**Motivation and Context**
This improves the situation described in #3418. That model now runs with the same performance as an equivalent model using 2D convolutions with "-o 2". Internally, MLAS just runs the convolution as a 2D convolution with height=1. On one AVX2 system running single-threaded, old was 900+ms, new was 225ms.

Using "-o 99", a 2D model can still run faster thanks to the NCHWc layout optimizer. This optimizer does not support reordering 1D tensors. With NCHWc, execution time drops to 185ms.

body:
@snnn @tracysh onnxruntime with dnnl EP is slow for Conv2D

```
import os
import time
os.environ["CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES"] = "-1"
os.environ['TF_KERAS'] = '1'
os.environ["OMP_NUM_THREADS"] = "1"
os.environ["MKL_NUM_THREADS"] = "1"
os.environ["OPENBLAS_NUM_THREADS"] = "1"

import keras
import numpy as np
import onnxmltools
import onnxruntime as ort
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import Input, Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, Dense

config = tf.compat.v1.ConfigProto(intra_op_parallelism_threads=1, inter_op_parallelism_threads=1)
tf.compat.v1.keras.backend.set_session(tf.compat.v1.Session(config=config))

x = np.random.randn(32, 256, 256, 30).astype('float32')
y = np.random.randn(32, 256, 256, 1).astype('float32')

o = i = Input(x.shape[1:], batch_size=32)
for n in range(5):
    o = Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same')(o)
o = Conv2D(1, (3, 3), padding='same')(o)
model = Model(inputs=[i], outputs=[o])
model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer='sgd')

model.fit(x, y, epochs=1, batch_size=32)
onnx_model = onnxmltools.convert_keras(model, target_opset=10)
onnxmltools.utils.save_model(onnx_model, 'rnn.onnx')

model.predict(x, batch_size=32)
ti = time.time()
model.predict(x, batch_size=32)
print('keras time: ', time.time() - ti)

so = ort.SessionOptions()
so.intra_op_num_threads = 1
sess = ort.InferenceSession("rnn.onnx", so)
for provider in sess.get_providers():
    sess.set_providers([provider])
    input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
    sess.run(None, {input_name: x})[0]
    ti = time.time()
    sess.run(None, {input_name: x})[0]
    print('onnx-' + provider, 'time: ', time.time() - ti)
```
```
keras time:  12.558596134185791
onnx-DnnlExecutionProvider time:  6.854508876800537
onnx-NupharExecutionProvider time:  7.801227807998657
onnx-CPUExecutionProvider time:  6.866337537765503
```
Hi @AStupidBear, does it mean onnxruntime CPUExecutionProvider is slower than keras on Conv2D too?

Hi @AStupidBear, the baseline runs with multiple CPUs, right? But you restrict onnxruntime to be singlethreaded, so the comparison isn't fair.  
On my machine, if both of them use multilple CPUs, the result is:
keras time:  2.618654727935791
onnxruntime time:2.15998

So onnxruntime is 20% faster.

rename.from: Conv1D is 10 times slower than tf.keras
rename.to: CPUExecutionProvider's Conv1D is 3 times slower than tf.keras

body: @snnn I have updated my script and now it's a fair comparison for the single-core case. We can see `DnnlExecutionProvider` is the fastest for `Conv1D` and `Conv2D`. `CPUExecutionProvider` is still much slower than `keras` for `Conv1D`.

@AStupidBear Have you remeasured the CPU EP performance using the latest master? PR #3425 improved the 1D convolution speed, but it is still a little short of DNNL. You should be able to get equivalent performance to DNNL if you reshape your convolutions as 2D with height=1. That will enable the existing CPU EP optimizer for a faster convolution path. There is additional work to the optimizer to also support 1D shapes, but that's a bigger project to do.
@tracysh No, I didn't try it yet but I believe it's much faster than.  May the poor support for 1D is also the root cause of issue #3548 ?
